ce:section.ce:para:
The practicality, reliability, and accuracy of the proposed sensing method for detecting dichloran were explored for real sample analysis. The dichloran residues were commonly found in various fruits, vegetables, and water resources. Thus, carrot, grape, and drinking water samples were selected for this work. These three real samples spiked with various standard dichloran concentrations (0.00, 10.00, 25.00, and 50.00 µM) were analyzed. Two techniques, HPLC and fluorescence methods, were used to measure the extracted dichloran. As shown in HPLC chromatograms, the dichloran peaks can be observed at 4.06 min in both the standard solutions and the extracted dichloran from the samples (Fig. 7
                        ). The fluorescence emission spectra of the NCDs, when combined with the extracted dichloran in real samples, demonstrated a close resemblance to the standalone fluorescence emission spectrum of the NCDs in the addition of dichloran. This alignment implies that the real samples had no discernible interference with the system (inset of Fig. 7). Furthermore, the recoveries of dichloran in real samples are within an acceptable range of 95.1–108.7 % with a relative standard deviation (RSD, n = 3) of less than 5.6 %, suggesting that the proposed fluorescence method exhibited good accuracy and reliability (Table 2
                        ). Additionally, according to the t-test and F-test calculations, there are no significant differences between these two methods at a 95 % confidence level. Therefore, our proposed sensing method demonstrates accuracy and practicality in determining dichloran in carrot, grape, and water samples.
